time_trend_data.indicator_description: West Nile virus (WNV) is an arbovirus which is transmitted through the bite of infected mosquitoes; in NYC, the mosquitoes that transmit WNV are primarily Culex pipiens as well as Culex restuans and Culex salinarius. While most people who are infected will not go on to develop symptoms, about 20% can experience mild or moderate illness and more rarely, neuroinvasive disease which can present as encephalitis or meningitis.  Most of the West Nile disease cases detected by the New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene represent neuroinvasive disease as these patients are more likely to seek care.   More specific West Nile viral disease data is available on the Health Department website.

info.info_how_calculated: Age-adjusted rates were calculated per 100,000 population using NYC DOHMH population estimates, modified from US Census Bureau interpolated intercensal estimates, updated April 2017.
info.info_source: NYC DOHMH Bureau of Communicable Disease
